@Oikofuge

Another consideration, which sometimes influenced dentists excessively in those days, was how slow local anaesthesia was to take effect. A small superficial filling might take half the time it took for the local to work. So you could see more patients if you didn't use local ... and that would occasionally push a dentist into taking a chance and pressing on with work that then caused pain.

Nowadays, I'm much impressed by the relative rapidity of onset (and offset) of modern local anaesthetic agents.

