On the assumption that my mention of the word itself triggered the emus, I'll need to censor myself.

There's a novel entitled "The ------ Hunt", using the word in its Biblical sense, written by Charles Sheffield. He later revised and reissued it with the title "The Mind Pool". He described how he'd been unsatisfied with the original ending, but I've always wondered if the title change was driven, at least in part, by the inadvertent comic effect of the original.

@Strudel Dad -- I'm voting for the Bugs/Fudd connection, too. 

What's funny is that OED citation is using it in the same way that Bugs did -- a sarcastic reference to a mighty hunter. 

But wherever the OED citation came from, I can pretty much guarantee it wasn't broadcast for decades on Saturday mornings. And since I and virtually no one in my generation or those following had any clue about the Biblical allusion, we grew up thinking it was an insult.

